{"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"572cc62e","metadata":{"id":"572cc62e"},"source":["# The Energy of Soil Water — Interactive Notebook\n","\n","**MOOC \"The Hydrology of Soil\" — Chapter 2**\n","\n","---\n","\n","Chapter 2 makes one central claim: the **mechanically stable configuration of\n","water in a soil is the one in which the smallest pores are filled and the\n","largest are empty**. From that single idea — together with the **Young–Laplace\n","relation** — follows a *unique* relationship between water content and suction:\n","the **soil water retention curve (SWRC)**.\n","\n","This notebook lets students *build* that curve themselves:\n","\n","1. start from a **pore-size distribution** — a bag of pores of different radii;\n","2. apply the rule \"**fill smallest first**\" and the **Young–Laplace relation**\n","   to obtain the retention curve θ(ψ) — the curve is *constructed*, not fitted;\n","3. compare this constructed curve with the standard **van Genuchten** formula;\n","4. explore the **energy \"Rosetta stone\"** — the same physical quantity written\n","   as chemical potential μ, as hydric potential Ψ (a pressure), and as\n","   hydraulic head h (a length).\n","\n","Run the cells in order (Shift+Enter). Plain NumPy — no special packages needed.\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"ddc7326f","metadata":{"id":"ddc7326f"},"source":["## 0 — Setup\n","\n","Run the package import cell below. If you have just updated the GitHub package, reinstall it first, then restart the runtime before continuing."]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":1,"id":"570a095e","metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"collapsed":true,"id":"570a095e","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779295364502,"user_tz":-60,"elapsed":19214,"user":{"displayName":"Lorenzo Duchi","userId":"05115729352499320280"}},"outputId":"233f9d90-b671-4fd5-c9d0-f620e34e5b13"},"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Collecting git+https://github.com/panzerotto/soil_course.git\n","  Cloning https://github.com/panzerotto/soil_course.git to /tmp/pip-req-build-szk2etx3\n","  Running command git clone --filter=blob:none --quiet https://github.com/panzerotto/soil_course.git /tmp/pip-req-build-szk2etx3\n","  Resolved https://github.com/panzerotto/soil_course.git to commit 15a4ab537065dcb406b18b305648221723661e4d\n","  Installing build dependencies ... \u001b[?25l\u001b[?25hdone\n","  Getting requirements to build wheel ... \u001b[?25l\u001b[?25hdone\n","  Preparing metadata (pyproject.toml) ... \u001b[?25l\u001b[?25hdone\n","Requirement already satisfied: numpy in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from soil-course==0.1.0) (2.0.2)\n","Requirement already satisfied: matplotlib in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from soil-course==0.1.0) (3.10.0)\n","Requirement already satisfied: scipy in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from soil-course==0.1.0) (1.16.3)\n","Requirement already satisfied: pandas in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from soil-course==0.1.0) (2.2.2)\n","Requirement already satisfied: openpyxl in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from soil-course==0.1.0) (3.1.5)\n","Requirement already satisfied: statsmodels in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from soil-course==0.1.0) (0.14.6)\n","Requirement already satisfied: contourpy>=1.0.1 in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from matplotlib->soil-course==0.1.0) (1.3.3)\n","Requirement already satisfied: cycler>=0.10 in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from matplotlib->soil-course==0.1.0) (0.12.1)\n","Requirement already satisfied: fonttools>=4.22.0 in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from matplotlib->soil-course==0.1.0) (4.62.1)\n","Requirement already satisfied: kiwisolver>=1.3.1 in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from matplotlib->soil-course==0.1.0) (1.5.0)\n","Requirement already satisfied: packaging>=20.0 in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from matplotlib->soil-course==0.1.0) (26.1)\n","Requirement already satisfied: pillow>=8 in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from matplotlib->soil-course==0.1.0) (11.3.0)\n","Requirement already satisfied: pyparsing>=2.3.1 in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from matplotlib->soil-course==0.1.0) (3.3.2)\n","Requirement already satisfied: python-dateutil>=2.7 in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from matplotlib->soil-course==0.1.0) (2.9.0.post0)\n","Requirement already satisfied: et-xmlfile in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from openpyxl->soil-course==0.1.0) (2.0.0)\n","Requirement already satisfied: pytz>=2020.1 in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from pandas->soil-course==0.1.0) (2025.2)\n","Requirement already satisfied: tzdata>=2022.7 in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from pandas->soil-course==0.1.0) (2026.1)\n","Requirement already satisfied: patsy>=0.5.6 in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from statsmodels->soil-course==0.1.0) (1.0.2)\n","Requirement already satisfied: six>=1.5 in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (from python-dateutil>=2.7->matplotlib->soil-course==0.1.0) (1.17.0)\n","Building wheels for collected packages: soil-course\n","  Building wheel for soil-course (pyproject.toml) ... \u001b[?25l\u001b[?25hdone\n","  Created wheel for soil-course: filename=soil_course-0.1.0-py3-none-any.whl size=10406 sha256=903e9cd0de755b944fa85d5bbbfcfa792009f9ddae955d5e1330f41c708cdd37\n","  Stored in directory: /tmp/pip-ephem-wheel-cache-eyecxflj/wheels/d1/cc/3a/6e11e3051820dbb8642dabb07e7fbe97d50387e4b7f07545bd\n","Successfully built soil-course\n","Installing collected packages: soil-course\n","Successfully installed soil-course-0.1.0\n","Setup complete\n"]}],"source":["try:\n","    from soil_course import *\n","    print(\"soil_course already available\")\n","except ModuleNotFoundError:\n","    !pip install git+https://github.com/panzerotto/soil_course.git\n","    from soil_course import *\n","\n","print(\"Setup complete\")"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"530b7008","metadata":{"id":"530b7008"},"source":["## 1 — The Young–Laplace relation: one pore, one suction\n","\n","A spherical air–water meniscus of radius $r$ in a pore sustains a pressure\n","jump\n","\n","$$|\\psi_p| \\;=\\; \\frac{2\\sigma}{\\rho_w g\\, r},$$\n","\n","where $\\psi_p$ is the **pressure head** (here expressed as a length of water\n","column). A *small* pore holds water at *large* suction; a *large* pore empties\n","at *small* suction. This is the hinge of the whole chapter.\n","\n","A pore of radius $r$ **stays full** as long as the applied suction $|\\psi|$ is\n","below its own $|\\psi_p(r)|$, and **drains** once $|\\psi|$ exceeds it.\n"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":2,"id":"ac61d03d","metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"ac61d03d","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779295379315,"user_tz":-60,"elapsed":46,"user":{"displayName":"Lorenzo Duchi","userId":"05115729352499320280"}},"outputId":"96f88022-5968-454f-8db3-de79a53d55ea"},"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["pore radius  1000.0 um  ->  empties at suction      0.015 m  (        1.5 cm )\n","pore radius   100.0 um  ->  empties at suction      0.148 m  (       14.8 cm )\n","pore radius    10.0 um  ->  empties at suction      1.484 m  (      148.4 cm )\n","pore radius     1.0 um  ->  empties at suction     14.842 m  (     1484.2 cm )\n","pore radius     0.1 um  ->  empties at suction    148.420 m  (    14842.0 cm )\n"]}],"source":["show_young_laplace_examples()"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"76b437fb","metadata":{"id":"76b437fb"},"source":["Notice the range: a 1 mm pore empties almost immediately (a few cm of\n","suction), while a 0.1 µm pore holds water to ~150 m of suction — the\n","conventional *wilting point*. The pore-size axis and the suction axis are the\n","**same axis**, read through Young–Laplace.\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"f9127935","metadata":{"id":"f9127935"},"source":["## 2 — A pore-size distribution\n","\n","Real soil has pores of many sizes. We describe them by a **lognormal\n","distribution** of pore radius — a simple, standard, two-parameter choice:\n","\n","* `r_median` — the median pore radius (µm);\n","* `sigma_p` — the spread (standard deviation of ln r): small = uniform pores,\n","  large = a wide mixture.\n","\n","The function below returns a discrete set of pore *classes*: their radii and\n","the **fraction of pore volume** each class contributes.\n"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":3,"id":"75bbb386","metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":501},"id":"75bbb386","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779295383268,"user_tz":-60,"elapsed":710,"user":{"displayName":"Lorenzo Duchi","userId":"05115729352499320280"}},"outputId":"a070ae4d-afc9-4d6c-c4df-2f1eed97818a"},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 900x504 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"source":["plot_pore_distribution(r_median=20.0, sigma_p=1.0)"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"652b95da","metadata":{"id":"652b95da"},"source":["## 3 — Building the retention curve: \"fill smallest first\"\n","\n","Now the central construction. At a given suction $|\\psi|$:\n","\n","* every pore with $|\\psi_p(r)| > |\\psi|$ — that is, every pore **smaller** than\n","  the critical radius $r^\\*(\\psi)$ — is **still full**;\n","* every larger pore is **empty**.\n","\n","So the water content at suction $|\\psi|$ is simply the **cumulative pore\n","volume up to** $r^\\*(\\psi)$:\n","\n","$$\\theta(\\psi) \\;=\\; \\theta_r + (\\theta_s-\\theta_r)\\!\\!\n","   \\sum_{r \\,<\\, r^\\*(\\psi)}\\! \\text{vol\\_frac}(r),\n","   \\qquad r^\\*(\\psi) = \\frac{2\\sigma}{\\rho_w g\\,|\\psi|}.$$\n","\n","This is the retention curve — and it was **constructed from the pore-size\n","distribution**, not fitted. The \"smallest filled, largest empty\" rule *is* the\n","SWRC.\n"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":4,"id":"b8b5b4cb","metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":442},"id":"b8b5b4cb","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779295388732,"user_tz":-60,"elapsed":1436,"user":{"displayName":"Lorenzo Duchi","userId":"05115729352499320280"}},"outputId":"55318598-06e8-4bae-f765-dff3746a1bbe"},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 1560x552 with 2 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"source":["plot_constructed_swrc()"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"399e582a","metadata":{"id":"399e582a"},"source":["Read the two panels together: the **right-hand curve is the left-hand\n","distribution, integrated**. A narrow pore distribution gives a steep,\n","step-like retention curve; a broad distribution gives a gentle one. Change the\n","spread and watch both panels move.\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"5ebd28c5","metadata":{"id":"5ebd28c5"},"source":["## 4 — Interactive: pores → retention curve\n","\n","Move the sliders and watch the retention curve being rebuilt:\n","\n","* **median pore radius** — slides the curve along the suction axis;\n","* **spread** — steep (uniform pores) vs gentle (broad mixture);\n","* **θr, θs** — the residual and saturated water contents.\n","\n","> Without `ipywidgets`, call `plot_constructed_swrc(...)` directly.\n"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":5,"id":"bf0a9f8a","metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":570,"referenced_widgets":["3d3b2936f3ac4aa489006bd8ac1ffd77","d4a30ee5f8314a5a97c606a902c8fcc1","a7a9faede89344f4b2c65ebd6f12d4f7","9c434f4285864cddb0b3c706878cba16","6297d59a789043878a20b062233becf3","e5a76f67c3f6438a9a7d87fa80d05893","c05e3d1ed5ea4cf5b5c0211f29e51dbb","65bb7d78aaf347ff88a1abf8d56ab996","f5cda15563e4484087906a8674589d60","4c45c39335494e8c87b0fe5ede48c649","394ceed32ffd4698a522fd040b3c4332","cb11fdfeec4e4d0f8ef64042a8d405ab","f550f7a7af2744b5b317e31f3b962b3e","d5ae6522edc54211bcad7420b144decd","f6a44bfda99f4b10a6fde89e9b8a8afb","26a8ba48d19f4609b2537ad89b475589"]},"id":"bf0a9f8a","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779295393751,"user_tz":-60,"elapsed":1077,"user":{"displayName":"Lorenzo Duchi","userId":"05115729352499320280"}},"outputId":"025478f9-375e-460d-8f18-0e460e06aa2f"},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["interactive(children=(FloatLogSlider(value=20.0, continuous_update=False, description='median r (um)', max=3.0…"],"application/vnd.jupyter.widget-view+json":{"version_major":2,"version_minor":0,"model_id":"3d3b2936f3ac4aa489006bd8ac1ffd77"}},"metadata":{}}],"source":["interactive_constructed_swrc()"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"60d92866","metadata":{"id":"60d92866"},"source":["## 5 — The constructed curve vs the van Genuchten formula\n","\n","The **van Genuchten** retention curve used in Chapters 3–5 is an empirical\n","formula:\n","\n","$$S_e(\\psi) = \\big[\\,1 + (\\alpha|\\psi|)^{n}\\,\\big]^{-m},\\qquad m = 1 - 1/n.$$\n","\n","It is *not* derived from a pore-size distribution — but it can be made to look\n","almost identical to one. The cell below overlays the **constructed** curve\n","(from the pores) and a **van Genuchten** curve, so students can see that the\n","empirical formula is a smooth stand-in for the pore-integration picture.\n"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":6,"id":"e9e6bb56","metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":597},"id":"e9e6bb56","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779295397540,"user_tz":-60,"elapsed":501,"user":{"displayName":"Lorenzo Duchi","userId":"05115729352499320280"}},"outputId":"b75701cc-2b5e-475f-f41c-367056908d2c"},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 960x600 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"source":["compare_curves(r_median=20.0, sigma_p=1.0, alpha=0.02, n=2.2)"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":7,"id":"5c66a8e1","metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":725,"referenced_widgets":["457b19ed1aa9422e809e89dcb50c3633","6ca26509afc54572935277c4682d49b3","f06cfb47ff1244689cce7f5387caf0f2","28cb06253640447dac950cfcd62f7574","cbe4441bf29946fd9ff96310e79bfb92","a122439ee6e9489cbab31e71c32924bb","e419de8f5c49462ca27a633a48a6e1ce","9b06d0a9921245aeb43a4e887a0019f3","da94042d10f54077a29b48c40cdd1256","722a27aa2f09456ea634b442f840d455","1d85547d827948af86536a508ea02a0f","fbb10be459ab420c8db633c2100e0eb4","042850ae014e4f888c76faffdd6b3445","4bed0b374882450182bf582ee312f872","d9a0ea8eb49e433f9bf0bef5881ffbad","348f867a2fb54ed589079681eede6d34"]},"id":"5c66a8e1","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779295400965,"user_tz":-60,"elapsed":820,"user":{"displayName":"Lorenzo Duchi","userId":"05115729352499320280"}},"outputId":"76481e06-388e-468d-e6d4-4cb9c01b8934"},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["interactive(children=(FloatLogSlider(value=20.0, continuous_update=False, description='median r (um)', max=3.0…"],"application/vnd.jupyter.widget-view+json":{"version_major":2,"version_minor":0,"model_id":"457b19ed1aa9422e809e89dcb50c3633"}},"metadata":{}}],"source":["interactive_compare_curves()"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"5abdb2dc","metadata":{"id":"5abdb2dc"},"source":["## 6 — The energy \"Rosetta stone\"\n","\n","Chapter 2 stresses that the energy of soil water is **one** physical quantity\n","written in **three** equivalent ways — different normalisations of the same\n","thing:\n","\n","| name | symbol | normalised per | units |\n","|------|--------|----------------|-------|\n","| chemical potential | μ − μ\\* | unit **mass** | J/kg |\n","| hydric potential   | Ψ | unit **volume** | Pa (= J/m³) |\n","| hydraulic / pressure head | h, ψ | unit **weight** | m of water |\n","\n","They are linked by the density of water:\n","\n","$$\\Psi = \\rho_w\\,(\\mu-\\mu^\\*),\\qquad h = \\frac{\\Psi}{\\rho_w g} = \\frac{\\mu-\\mu^\\*}{g}.$$\n","\n","The converter below lets students enter a value in any one of the three and\n","read it back in the other two.\n"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":8,"id":"829d5cfd","metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"829d5cfd","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779295404443,"user_tz":-60,"elapsed":8,"user":{"displayName":"Lorenzo Duchi","userId":"05115729352499320280"}},"outputId":"5b195a0d-ecfe-4683-dc1c-3599c9bb8596"},"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["The same soil-water energy state expressed three ways:\n","\n","  hydraulic head      h   = -150.0000 m  ( -15000.0 cm )\n","  hydric potential    Psi = -1.472e+06 Pa  ( -1471.50 kPa )\n","  chemical potential  mu  = -1471.5000 J/kg\n"]}],"source":["show_energy_rosetta(value=-150.0, unit=\"head_m\")"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":9,"id":"9725744a","metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":133,"referenced_widgets":["26ad9f5012b7457a92104eaaa6361239","b9d2e3dba23b4f69b2c8e86055f8703c","9a467660ebbb4b03b0049d3ba8bbdd03","4a6d380a00b04e6aa5a89ce888ce41d1","8944bc1d55b44aa0bd060744e53fa057","ab29c8b9d96a494d96ce29f1bb940e1e","31257edf06b14f43ba9e8ef775577f47","542ea716466f4a50b94956355a6a3a4b","5543299166f4465ea8444a0a6fda1fe7","9bd1b1295b5c44ab8e25c0662e4078d7"]},"id":"9725744a","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1779295406993,"user_tz":-60,"elapsed":32,"user":{"displayName":"Lorenzo Duchi","userId":"05115729352499320280"}},"outputId":"eb13ec0f-71b2-416f-bc84-52be724dd2bf"},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["interactive(children=(FloatText(value=-150.0, description='value'), Dropdown(description='given as', options=(…"],"application/vnd.jupyter.widget-view+json":{"version_major":2,"version_minor":0,"model_id":"26ad9f5012b7457a92104eaaa6361239"}},"metadata":{}}],"source":["interactive_energy_rosetta()"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"0fbc80c1","metadata":{"id":"0fbc80c1"},"source":["## Exercises\n","\n","1. **Pore size sets the suction.** Using `young_laplace_head`, find the pore\n","   radius that empties at exactly 1 m of suction. Which textural fraction\n","   (sand / silt / clay pores) does that radius belong to?\n","\n","2. **The distribution is the curve.** In Section 4, set the spread to a small\n","   value (`sigma_p = 0.3`) and then a large one (`sigma_p = 2.0`), keeping the\n","   median fixed. Describe how the *steepness* of the retention curve follows\n","   the *width* of the pore distribution. Why must this be so?\n","\n","3. **Empirical vs constructed.** In Section 5, try to match the constructed\n","   curve with van Genuchten by tuning α and n. Which van Genuchten parameter\n","   plays the role of the median pore radius? Which plays the role of the\n","   spread?\n","\n","4. **Same state, three numbers.** A tensiometer reads a suction of 3 m of\n","   water. Express this as a hydric potential in kPa and as a chemical potential\n","   in J/kg. Then explain, in one sentence, why all three numbers describe a\n","   single physical condition.\n","\n","5. **The smallest-filled rule.** In your own words, explain why the\n","   *minimum-energy* configuration of water in a soil is the one with the\n","   smallest pores full — and why that is what makes θ(ψ) a single-valued\n","   curve. (This is the heart of Chapter 2.)\n","\n","---\n","\n","*Companion to the MOOC \"The Hydrology of Soil\", Chapter 2 — The energy of soil\n","water. Licensed CC BY-SA, consistent with the lecture slides.*\n"]}],"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","language":"python","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python","version":"3"},"colab":{"provenance":[]},"widgets":{"application/vnd.jupyter.widget-state+json":{"3d3b2936f3ac4aa489006bd8ac1ffd77":{"model_module":"@jupyter-widgets/controls","model_name":"VBoxModel","model_module_version":"1.5.0","state":{"_dom_classes":["widget-interact"],"_model_module":"@jupyter-widgets/controls","_model_module_version":"1.5.0","_model_name":"VBoxModel","_view_count":null,"_view_module":"@jupyter-widgets/controls","_view_module_ve